						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">so, when accessing address $2000, for example, A13 is 1. When inverted, it becomes 0. And then, 0 goes into /CE of the chip, and if 0 is "false", inverted it would become true, meanign that the chip would be enabled when accessing that memory.</div>
<br />
<br />That is correct - by connecting PPU /A13 to VRAM /CE, you cause VRAM to be enabled for $2000-$3FFF. PPU A13 typically gets connected to CHR ROM|RAM /CE, which enables it for $0000-$1FFF.</div>

					
